h3. Extracting the Data by Request

* In the previous example, we used the default GET method to send form input to the server. We also assumed the register_globals directive in the php.ini file was turned "On," allowing PHP to create local variables with the form data.
* In the following example, we assume that register_globals is turned "Off" (the recommended and default setting) and that the method is POST, the more commonly used method when working with form input.
* This method sends the form input as a message body in the HTTP header to the server and does not append the data to the URL in the browser. Even though the input data is sent using a different method, it is received in the same URL-encoded format.
* When register_globals is turned off, we must use built-in PHP special variables, called "super-global arrays", to access the form information.
* Because we do not cover arrays until later in the course, we will use the PHP extract() function and the super-global array $_REQUEST to create local variables to hold input data from the form.
* The $_REQUEST array contains all of the input data for both GET and POST methods. Once extract($_REQUEST) is executed the HTML form's parameters will be assigned to PHP variables of the same names.
